{
  "document_id": "prov-21",
  "title": "Proverbs 21",
  "type": "study-bible",
  "translation": "Oxford",
  "blocks": [
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-heading-22",
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "22"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-2",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 2,
      "text": "All deeds are right in the sight of the doer, but the Lord weighs the heart."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-2",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "21.1–2: God directs and examines human hearts. , channels used to irrigate dry land (cf. Isa 32.2). , see 16.2n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 1,
      "verse_end": 2
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-3",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 3,
      "text": "To do righteousness and justice is more acceptable to the Lord than sacrifice."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-4",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 4,
      "text": "Haughty eyes and a proud heart— the lamp of the wicked—are sin."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-3",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "4 : , see 13.9n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 4,
      "verse_end": 4
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-5",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 5,
      "text": "The plans of the diligent lead surely to abundance, but everyone who is hasty comes only to want."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-6",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 6,
      "text": "The getting of treasures by a lying tongue is a fleeting vapor and a snare of death."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-5",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "6 : Unjustly acquired wealth, see 1.18–19n. (Heb “hebel”), i.e., ephemeral (e.g., Ps 144.4; Job 7.16; Eccl 1.2 [“vanity”]).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 6,
      "verse_end": 6
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-7",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 7,
      "text": "The violence of the wicked will sweep them away, because they refuse to do what is just."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-4",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "5–7 : Comparisons of diligent and deceitful and violent means and ends.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 5,
      "verse_end": 7
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-6",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "7 : See 10.2–3n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 7,
      "verse_end": 7
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-8",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 8,
      "text": "The way of the guilty is crooked, but the conduct of the pure is right."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-9",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 9,
      "text": "It is better to live in a corner of the housetop than in a house shared with a contentious wife."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-7",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "9 : , see 19.13–14n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 9,
      "verse_end": 9
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-10",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 10,
      "text": "The souls of the wicked desire evil; their neighbors find no mercy in their eyes."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-11",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 11,
      "text": "When a scoffer is punished, the simple become wiser; when the wise are instructed, they increase in knowledge."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-8",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "11 : See 19.25.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 11,
      "verse_end": 11
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-12",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 12,
      "text": "The Righteous One observes the house of the wicked; he casts the wicked down to ruin."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-9",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "12 : , i.e., God; see 22.12; Isa 24.16.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 12,
      "verse_end": 12
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-13",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 13,
      "text": "If you close your ear to the cry of the poor, you will cry out and not be heard."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-10",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "13 : See 14.31n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 13,
      "verse_end": 13
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-14",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 14,
      "text": "A gift in secret averts anger; and a concealed bribe in the bosom, strong wrath."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-11",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "14 : , see 17.8n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 14,
      "verse_end": 14
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-15",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 15,
      "text": "When justice is done, it is a joy to the righteous, but dismay to evildoers."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-16",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 16,
      "text": "Whoever wanders from the way of understanding will rest in the assembly of the dead."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-12",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "16 : , i.e., Sheol, see 1.12n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 16,
      "verse_end": 16
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-17",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 17,
      "text": "Whoever loves pleasure will suffer want; whoever loves wine and oil will not be rich."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-18",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 18,
      "text": "The wicked is a ransom for the righteous, and the faithless for the upright."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-13",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "18 : , a payment to buy someone out of trouble; the person can be innocent (e.g., 6.35; Ex 30.12,15–16; Num 31.50; Isa 43.3). , see 2.22n. See 11.8.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 18,
      "verse_end": 18
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-19",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 19,
      "text": "It is better to live in a desert land than with a contentious and fretful wife."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-14",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "19 : See v. 9.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 19,
      "verse_end": 19
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-20",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 20,
      "text": "Precious treasure remains in the house of the wise, but the fool devours it."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-21",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 21,
      "text": "Whoever pursues righteousness and kindness will find life and honor."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-22",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 22,
      "text": "One wise person went up against a city of warriors and brought down the stronghold in which they trusted."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-15",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "22 : Wisdom proves stronger than physical and military might, see 20.18; 24.5–6; Eccl 9.13–18.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 22,
      "verse_end": 22
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-23",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 23,
      "text": "To watch over mouth and tongue is to keep out of trouble."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-16",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "23 : See 13.3; 18.21.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 23,
      "verse_end": 23
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-24",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 24,
      "text": "The proud, haughty person, named “Scoffer,” acts with arrogant pride."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-17",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "24 : , see 1.22n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 24,
      "verse_end": 24
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-25",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 25,
      "text": "The craving of the lazy person is fatal, for lazy hands refuse to labor."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-18",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "25 : , see 6.9–11n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 25,
      "verse_end": 25
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-26",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 26,
      "text": "All day long the wicked covet, but the righteous give and do not hold back."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-27",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 27,
      "text": "The sacrifice of the wicked is an abomination; how much more when brought with evil intent."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-19",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "27 : , see 3.32n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 27,
      "verse_end": 27
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-28",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 28,
      "text": "A false witness will perish, but a good listener will testify successfully."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-20",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "28 : , see 12.17n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 28,
      "verse_end": 28
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-29",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 29,
      "text": "The wicked put on a bold face, but the upright give thought to their ways."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-21",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "29 : , i.e., defiant, see 7.13.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 29,
      "verse_end": 29
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-30",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 30,
      "text": "No wisdom, no understanding, no counsel, can avail against the Lord."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-31",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 31,
      "text": "The horse is made ready for the day of battle, but the victory belongs to the Lord."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-1",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "10.1–22.16: The proverbs of Solomon. Comprised predominantly of two-line proverbs, the oldest section of Proverbs can be divided into 10.1–15.33, which features antithetical proverbs, and 16.1–22.16, which includes a mix of proverbial forms.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 1,
      "verse_end": 31
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-21-h1kj-22",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "30–31 : Limits of human wisdom before God, see 16.1–9; 19.21.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 21
      },
      "verse_start": 30,
      "verse_end": 31
    }
  ]
}